			</xsd:choice>
			<xsd:attribute name="name" type="xsd:string" use="required"/>
			<xsd:attribute name="template" type="xsd:string"/>
		</xsd:complexType>
	</xsd:element>
	<xsd:element name="per-vertex-shape-default">
		<xsd:annotation>
			<xsd:documentation>Template/default values for per-vertex-shape elements. Defines default tags,
collision filters, margin settings, and weight-threshold behavior for following
per-vertex-shape elements unless overridden. As XML is parsed in document order,
redefining per-vertex-shape-default affects subsequent per-vertex-shape entries.
Optional attributes name/extends (via defaults attributeGroup) support named
templates and inheritance.
</xsd:documentation>
		</xsd:annotation>
		<xsd:complexType>
			<xsd:choice maxOccurs="unbounded">
				<xsd:element ref="margin"/>
				<xsd:element ref="tag"/>
				<xsd:element ref="shared"/>
				<xsd:element ref="no-collide-with-tag"/>
				<xsd:element ref="can-collide-with-tag"/>
				<xsd:element ref="no-collide-with-bone"/>
				<xsd:element ref="can-collide-with-bone"/>
				<xsd:element ref="weight-threshold"/>
				<xsd:element ref="disable-tag"/>
				<xsd:element ref="disable-priority"/>
			</xsd:choice>
			<xsd:attributeGroup ref="defaults"/>
		</xsd:complexType>
	</xsd:element>
	<xsd:element name="shape">
		<xsd:annotation>
			<xsd:documentation>Defines a collision shape that Bullet uses for physics simulation. Can be used
in three ways:
1) Top-level shape definition with name attribute: stores the shape in a named
registry for reuse via &lt;ref&gt; elements
2) Inline inside &lt;bone&gt; or &lt;bone-default&gt;: directly attaches the
shape to that bone
3) Nested inside a &lt;shape type="compound"&gt;: creates a composite shape from
multiple child shapes

Required attribute: type (box|sphere|capsule|hull|cylinder|compound). Optional
attribute: name (required for top-level definitions; stores shape for reuse).
Optional attribute: transform (used for positioning shapes within compound
shapes).

Child elements depend on the shape type:
- box: requires halfExtend; optional margin
- sphere: requires radius; no margin support
- capsule: requires radius and height; optional margin
- cylinder: requires radius and height; optional margin (added to radius)
- hull: requires one or more point children (x y z coordinates)
- compound: contains ref elements and/or nested shape elements

IMPORTANT: The shape type directly controls Bullet physics behavior. Example: A
breasts bone with a &lt;shape type="capsule"&gt; will collide smoothly and
appear elastic/bouncy, while a &lt;shape type="hull"&gt; fitted to the exact
mesh will constrain collisions more tightly to match the visual geometry. Choose
the shape type based on desired physics feel, not just accuracy.
</xsd:documentation>
		</xsd:annotation>
		<xsd:complexType>
			<xsd:choice minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
				<xsd:element ref="halfExtend">
					<xsd:annotation>
						<xsd:documentation>Axis-aligned half-extents (half-dimensions) vector. For type box only. Vector3
format: x y z (in game units). All components should be positive. Example:
&lt;halfExtend&gt;0.5 0.3 0.2&lt;/halfExtend&gt; creates a box centered at
origin with dimensions 1.0 x 0.6 x 0.4. Required for box shapes; optional for
others (will be ignored).
</xsd:documentation>
					</xsd:annotation>
				</xsd:element>
				<xsd:element name="margin" type="posFloat">
					<xsd:annotation>
						<xsd:documentation>Collision margin (buffer around shape for continuous collision detection). For
types box, hull and cylinder. Optional. Positive value in game units. If
undefined, defaults to 0. For cylinder: margin is added to the radius
(effectively increasing cylinder thickness). For box and hull: margin expands
the shape symmetrically in all directions. Recommended: small value like
0.01-0.05 to improve collision stability.
</xsd:documentation>
					</xsd:annotation>
				</xsd:element>
				<xsd:element name="radius" type="posFloat">
					<xsd:annotation>
						<xsd:documentation>Radius (half-width) of sphere, capsule, or cylinder shapes. For types sphere,
capsule and cylinder. Optional. Positive value in game units. If undefined,
defaults to 0 (degenerate shape). For sphere: radius from center to surface. For
capsule: radius around the central axis (cylinder + hemispherical caps). For
cylinder: radius of the circular cross-section.
</xsd:documentation>
					</xsd:annotation>
				</xsd:element>
				<xsd:element name="height" type="posFloat">
					<xsd:annotation>
						<xsd:documentation>Height along the primary axis. For types capsule and cylinder. Optional.
Positive value in game units. If undefined, defaults to 0 (degenerate shape).
For capsule: distance between the centers of the two hemispherical caps (along Y
axis). For cylinder: distance from top face to bottom face (along Y axis). The
shape extends from -height/2 to +height/2 in local Y coordinates.
</xsd:documentation>
					</xsd:annotation>
				</xsd:element>
				<xsd:element ref="point">
					<xsd:annotation>
						<xsd:documentation>Vertex coordinate for convex hull shape. For type hull only. Vector3 format: x y
z. Define multiple &lt;point&gt; elements to create the hull. Bullet will
compute the convex hull from all points you provide. Minimum 4 points required
to form a valid convex hull (tetrahedron). Example: &lt;point&gt;0.0 0.0
0.0&lt;/point&gt; &lt;point&gt;1.0 0.0 0.0&lt;/point&gt; etc.
</xsd:documentation>
					</xsd:annotation>
				</xsd:element>
				<xsd:element ref="child">
					<xsd:annotation>
						<xsd:documentation>Reference to a named shape (via name attribute). For type compound only.
References a previously defined top-level &lt;shape name="xyz"&gt; element.
Optional transform attribute positions the referenced shape within the compound.
</xsd:documentation>
					</xsd:annotation>
				</xsd:element>
			</xsd:choice>
			<xsd:attribute name="name" type="xsd:string">
				<xsd:annotation>
					<xsd:documentation>Optional name identifier for the shape. Usage depends on context:
1) Top-level shapes: name is recommended (or required if you want to reuse the
shape elsewhere). Stores shape in a named registry for reuse via &lt;shape
type="ref" name="xyz"/&gt;.
2) Inline shapes (inside bone/bone-default): name is optional. Only specify if
you want to store it for later reuse.
3) Reference shapes (type="ref"): name is required. Must match a previously
defined top-level shape name.
4) Nested shapes (inside compound): name is typically unused (position
controlled by transform attribute).
</xsd:documentation>
				</xsd:annotation>
			</xsd:attribute>
			<xsd:attribute name="type" type="shapeType" use="required">
				<xsd:annotation>
					<xsd:documentation>Required. Shape type (box|sphere|capsule|hull|cylinder|compound|ref).
- box: axis-aligned box; requires halfExtend
- sphere: sphere; requires radius
- capsule: cylinder with hemispherical caps; requires radius and height
- hull: convex hull from point cloud; requires one or more point children
- cylinder: open-ended cylinder; requires radius and height; margin is added to
radius
- compound: composite of child shapes (ref elements or nested shape elements)
- ref: reference to a previously defined named shape; requires name attribute
pointing to existing shape
</xsd:documentation>
				</xsd:annotation>
			</xsd:attribute>
		</xsd:complexType>
	</xsd:element>
	<xsd:element name="stiffspring-constraint">
		<xsd:annotation>
			<xsd:documentation>Distance-based spring constraint between two bones (bodyA and bodyB).

This is a custom radial distance solver: every simulation step, runtime computes
the current bone-to-bone distance and applies spring + damping forces along that
live direction.

Core spring equation: force = stiffness * (distance - equilibriumPoint) +
damping * velocity

Distance bounds:
- minDistanceFactor scales the initial bodyA/bodyB distance to create the lower
distance limit
- maxDistanceFactor scales the initial bodyA/bodyB distance to create the upper
distance limit
- equilibrium (0..1) sets equilibriumPoint by interpolation between minDistance
and maxDistance

IMPORTANT: This is not generic-constraint. You can approximate a tether-like
effect with generic-constraint in some setups, but you cannot guarantee exact
replication of this custom radial distance solver behavior.
</xsd:documentation>
		</xsd:annotation>
		<xsd:complexType>
			<xsd:choice minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
				<xsd:element ref="minDistanceFactor"/>
				<xsd:element ref="maxDistanceFactor"/>
				<xsd:element ref="stiffness"/>
				<xsd:element ref="damping"/>
				<xsd:element ref="equilibrium"/>
			</xsd:choice>
			<xsd:attribute name="bodyA" type="xsd:string" use="required">
				<xsd:annotation>
					<xsd:documentation>bodyA is required and must contain a bone name. Bone declaration is optional,
see the bone documentation.
</xsd:documentation>
				</xsd:annotation>
			</xsd:attribute>
			<xsd:attribute name="bodyB" type="xsd:string" use="required">
				<xsd:annotation>
					<xsd:documentation>bodyB is required and must contain a bone name. Bone declaration is optional,
see the bone documentation.
</xsd:documentation>
				</xsd:annotation>
			</xsd:attribute>
			<xsd:attribute name="template" type="xsd:string"/>
		</xsd:complexType>
	</xsd:element>
	<xsd:element name="stiffspring-constraint-default">
		<xsd:annotation>
			<xsd:documentation>Template/default values for stiffspring-constraint elements. Defines default
min/max distance factors, stiffness, damping, and equilibrium interpolation for
following stiffspring constraints unless overridden. As XML is parsed in
document order, redefining stiffspring-constraint-default affects subsequent
stiffspring-constraint elements. Templates can be named and inherited via
name/extends.
</xsd:documentation>
		</xsd:annotation>
		<xsd:complexType>
			<xsd:choice minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
				<xsd:element ref="minDistanceFactor"/>
				<xsd:element ref="maxDistanceFactor"/>
				<xsd:element ref="stiffness"/>
				<xsd:element ref="damping"/>
				<xsd:element ref="equilibrium"/>
			</xsd:choice>
			<xsd:attribute name="name" type="xsd:string">
				<xsd:annotation>
					<xsd:documentation>The name of a stiffspring-constraint-default is optional. If it isn't set, "" is
the name. As the xml is interpreted line by line, you can redefine the default
so that it impacts the following stiffspring-constraints.
</xsd:documentation>
				</xsd:annotation>
			</xsd:attribute>
			<xsd:attribute name="extends" type="xsd:string"/>
		</xsd:complexType>
	</xsd:element>

	<!-- ############################################################ -->
	<!-- complexTypes -->
	<!-- ############################################################ -->

	<xsd:complexType name="vector3">
		<xsd:simpleContent>
			<xsd:extension base="xsd:string">
				<xsd:attribute name="x" type="flexFloat" use="required"/>
				<xsd:attribute name="y" type="flexFloat" use="required"/>
				<xsd:attribute name="z" type="flexFloat" use="required"/>
			</xsd:extension>
		</xsd:simpleContent>
	</xsd:complexType>
	<xsd:complexType name="limitedVector3">
		<xsd:simpleContent>
			<xsd:extension base="xsd:string">
				<xsd:attribute name="x" type="factor" use="required"/>
				<xsd:attribute name="y" type="factor" use="required"/>
				<xsd:attribute name="z" type="factor" use="required"/>
			</xsd:extension>
		</xsd:simpleContent>
	</xsd:complexType>
	<xsd:complexType name="quaternion">
		<xsd:simpleContent>
			<xsd:extension base="xsd:string">
				<xsd:attribute name="x" type="flexFloat" use="required"/>
				<xsd:attribute name="y" type="flexFloat" use="required"/>
				<xsd:attribute name="z" type="flexFloat" use="required"/>
				<xsd:attribute name="w" type="flexFloat" use="required"/>
			</xsd:extension>
		</xsd:simpleContent>
	</xsd:complexType>
	<xsd:complexType name="transform">
		<xsd:choice minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
			<xsd:element name="basis" type="quaternion">
				<xsd:annotation>
					<xsd:documentation>This is a quaternion. If it's set with a length of zero, it will be set as
Identity (0, 0, 0, 1). Rotational COM.
</xsd:documentation>
				</xsd:annotation>
			</xsd:element>
			<xsd:element name="basis-axis-angle">
				<xsd:annotation>
					<xsd:documentation>This is a transformation rotation with an angle around an axis defined by a
vector. If the vector (x, y, z) is (0, 0, 0), it will be set as (1,0,0), and the
angle will be set at 0 whatever its value. The length of the vector isn't
important as it will be normalized. The angle is in radians.
</xsd:documentation>
				</xsd:annotation>
				<xsd:complexType>
					<xsd:simpleContent>
						<xsd:extension base="xsd:string">
							<xsd:attribute name="x" type="flexFloat" use="required"/>
							<xsd:attribute name="y" type="flexFloat" use="required"/>
							<xsd:attribute name="z" type="flexFloat" use="required"/>
							<xsd:attribute name="angle" type="flexFloat" use="required"/>
						</xsd:extension>
					</xsd:simpleContent>
				</xsd:complexType>
			</xsd:element>
			<xsd:element name="origin" type="vector3"/>
		</xsd:choice>
	</xsd:complexType>
	<xsd:complexType name="lerp">
		<xsd:all>
			<xsd:element name="translationLerp" type="flexFloat" minOccurs="0"/>
			<xsd:element name="rotationLerp" type="flexFloat" minOccurs="0"/>
		</xsd:all>
	</xsd:complexType>
</xsd:schema>
